Definition 2.6. An $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functor between non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$categories $F:{\mathcal{C}}_{1}\to{\mathcal{C}}_{2}$ is given by the following data: 1) A map of classes of objects $F:Ob({\mathcal{C}}_{1})\to Ob({\mathcal{C}}_{2}).$ 2) For any finite sequence of objects $X_{0},\dots,X_{n}$ in ${\mathcal{C}}_{1},$ a morphism of graded vector spaces $f_{n}:\bigotimes\limits_{0\leq i\leq n-1}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{i+1})\to% \operatorname{Hom}(F(X_{0}),F(X_{n}))[1-n].$ It is required that for any finite collection of objects $X_{0},\dots,X_{N},$ $N\geq 0,$ the sequence $f_{n},$ $n\geq 1,$ defines an $A_{\infty}\text{-}$morphism $\bigoplus\limits_{0\leq i,j\leq N}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{j})\to\bigoplus% \limits_{0\leq i,j\leq N}\operatorname{Hom}(F(X_{i}),F(X_{j})).$
Definition 2.18. An $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ between $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories is called quasi-equivalence if: a) For any pair $(X_{1},X_{2})\in{\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{2},$ the map $f_{1}:\operatorname{Hom}(X_{1},X_{2})\to\operatorname{Hom}(F(X_{1}),F(X_{2}))$ is a quasi-isomorphism. b) Each object $Y$ of ${\mathcal{D}}$ is quasi-isomorphic to some $F(X),$ $X\in Ob({\mathcal{C}}).$
Definition 2.2. An $A_{\infty}\text{-}$ morphism of non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$algebras $A\to B$ is a morphism of the corresponding non-counital DG coalgebras $T_{+}(A[1])\to T_{+}(B[1]).$
Definition 2.13. An $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functor between non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ is given by the following data: 1) A map of classes of objects $F:Ob({\mathcal{C}})\to Ob({\mathcal{D}}),$ such that $F({\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{n})\subset{\mathcal{D}}_{tr}^{n}.$ 2) For any finite transversal sequence of objects $X_{0},\dots,X_{n}$ in ${\mathcal{C}},$ a morphism of graded vector spaces $f_{n}:\bigotimes\limits_{0\leq i\leq n-1}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{i+1})\to% \operatorname{Hom}(F(X_{0}),F(X_{n}))[1-n].$ It is required that for any transversal sequence of objects $X_{0},\dots,X_{N},$ $N\geq 0,$ the sequence $f_{n},$ $n\geq 1,$ defines an $A_{\infty}\text{-}$morphism $\bigoplus\limits_{0\leq i<j\leq N}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{j})\to\bigoplus% \limits_{0\leq i<j\leq N}\operatorname{Hom}(F(X_{i}),F(X_{j})).$
Definition 3.6. Define a ($\mathbb{Z}$- or $\mathbb{Z}/2$-)graded pre-category as an $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-category with $m_{n}=0$ for $n\neq 2.$ Define a functor between graded pre-categories to be an $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functor with $f_{n}=0$ for $n\neq 1.$ We say that such a functor is an equivalence if it is a quasi-equivalence of $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories.
Definition 2.7. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$category, and $X\in Ob({\mathcal{C}}).$ A morphism $e\in\operatorname{Hom}^{0}(X,X)$ is called a) a strict identity if $m_{2}(f,e)=f,$ $m_{2}(e,g)=g,$ for $n\neq 2$ $m_{n}(f_{1},\dots,f_{i-1},e,f_{i+1},\dots,f_{n})=0$ for any morphisms $f,g,f_{j}$ such that the equalities make sense. In this case we put $1_{X}:=e.$ b) a weak identity if $m_{1}(e)=0,$ and for any closed morphisms $f:X\to Y,$ $g:Z\to X,$ we have that in $H({\mathcal{C}})$ $\bar{e}\cdot\bar{g}=\bar{g},$ $\bar{f}\cdot\bar{e}=\bar{f}.$
Definition 2.16. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ and ${\mathcal{D}}$ be $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories. An $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ is an $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functor between the corresponding non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories which takes quasi-isomorphisms in ${\mathcal{C}}$ to quasi-isomorphisms in ${\mathcal{D}}.$
Definition 3.13. Let $F,F^{\prime}:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ be $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functors between $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories, such that $F(X)=F^{\prime}(X)$ for each $X\in Ob({\mathcal{C}}).$ A homotopy $H$ between $f$ and $f^{\prime}$ is a collection of maps $h_{n}:\bigotimes\limits_{1\leq i\leq n}\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(X_{i% -1},X_{i})\to\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{D}}}(F(X_{0}),F(X_{n}))$ of degree $-n,$ for all transversal sequences $(X_{0},\dots,X_{n}),$ satisfying the following property. For each transversal sequence $(X_{0},\dots,X_{N})\in{\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{n+1},$ we have that the maps $h_{n}$ define a homotopy between the restricted $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functors $F,F^{\prime}:\bigoplus\limits_{i<j}\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(X_{i},X_% {j})\to F,F^{\prime}:\bigoplus\limits_{i<j}\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{D}}}(% F(X_{i}),F(X_{j})).$
Definition 2.12. A non-unital $\mathbb{Z}$(resp. $\mathbb{Z}/2$)-graded $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is the following data: a) A class of objects $Ob({\mathcal{C}}),$ b) For any $n\geq 1$ a subclass ${\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{n}\subset Ob({\mathcal{C}})^{n}$ of transversal sequences. It is required that ${\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{1}=Ob({\mathcal{C}}).$ c) For each pair $(X_{1},X_{2})\in{\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{2},$ a graded vector space $\operatorname{Hom}(X_{1},X_{2}).$ d) For a transversal sequence of objects $X_{0},\dots,X_{n},$ a map of graded vector spaces $m_{n}:\bigotimes\limits_{0\leq i\leq n-1}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{i+1})\to% \operatorname{Hom}(X_{0},X_{n})[2-n].$ It is required that each subsequence $(X_{i_{1}},X_{i_{2}},\dots,X_{i_{l}}),$ $0\leq i_{1}<i_{2}<\dots<i_{l}\leq n$ of a transversal sequence $(X_{0},\dots,X_{N})$ is transversal, and that the graded vector space $\bigoplus\limits_{0\leq i<j\leq N}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{j})$ with operations $m_{n}$ becomes a non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$algebra.
Definition 4.3. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be an $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-category. Define the $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-category ${\mathcal{C}}^{pre-tr}$ of twisted complexes over ${\mathcal{C}}$ as follows: 1) Objects of ${\mathcal{C}}^{pre-tr}$ are pairs $(S,\alpha),$ where $S$ is some transversal sequence in $\widetilde{{\mathcal{C}}},$ and $\alpha\in\operatorname{End}_{+}(S)^{1}$ is a Maurer-Cartan solution. 2) The sequence $((S_{1},\alpha_{1}),\dots,(S_{n},\alpha_{n}))\in({\mathcal{C}}^{pre-tr})^{n}$ is transversal iff the sequence $(S_{1},\dots,S_{n})$ is transversal in $\widetilde{{\mathcal{C}}}.$ 3) For a transversal pair $((S_{1},\alpha_{1}),(S_{2},\alpha_{2}))$ in ${\mathcal{C}}^{pre-tr},$ we put $\operatorname{Hom}((S_{1},\alpha_{1}),(S_{2},\alpha_{2}))=\bigoplus\limits_{X% \in S_{1},Y\in S_{2}}\operatorname{Hom}(X,Y).$ 4) For a transversal sequence, $((S_{0},\alpha_{0}),\dots,(S_{n},\alpha_{n}))\in({\mathcal{C}}^{pre-tr})_{tr}^% {n+1},$ and homogeneous morphisms $x_{i}\in\operatorname{Hom}((S_{i-1},\alpha_{i-1}),(S_{i},\alpha_{i}))$ we put $m_{n}(x_{n},\dots,x_{1})=\sum\limits_{k_{0},\dots,k_{n}\geq 0}(-1)^{\epsilon}m% _{n+k_{0}+\dots+k_{n}}(\alpha_{n}^{k_{n}},x_{n},\alpha_{n-1}^{k_{n-1}},\dots,x% _{1},\alpha_{0}^{k_{0}}),$ where $\epsilon=\sum\limits_{n\geq i>j\geq 0}(\deg(x_{i})+k_{i})k_{j}+\sum\limits_{i=% 0}^{n}\frac{k_{i}(k_{i}+1)}{2}+\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n}ik_{i}.$
Definition 3.4. An $A_{\infty}$-(pre-)category is called minimal if $m_{1}=0.$
Definition 2.9. An $A_{\infty}\text{-}$functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ between $A_{\infty}\text{-}$categories with strict (resp. weak) identity morphisms is called strictly (resp. weakly) unital if it preserves strict units and $f_{n}(g_{1},\dots,1_{X},\dots,g_{n})=0$ whenever $n>1$ (resp. if it preserves weak identity morphisms).
Definition 2.1. A structure of a non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$algebra on $A$ is given by degree $+1$ coderivation $b:T_{+}(A[1])\to T_{+}(A[1]),$ such that $b^{2}=0.$ Here $T_{+}(A[1])=\bigoplus\limits_{n\geq 1}A[1]^{\otimes n}$ is a cofree tensor coalgebra.
Definition 2.14. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a non-unital $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-category, and $(X_{1},X_{2})\in{\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{2}.$ A closed morphism $f\in\operatorname{Hom}^{0}(X_{1},X_{2})$ is called a quasi-isomorphism if for any objects $X_{0}$ and $X_{3}$ such that $(X_{0},X_{1},X_{2})\in{\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{3},$ $(X_{1},X_{2},X_{3})\in{\mathcal{C}}_{tr}^{3},$ one has that the maps $m_{2}(f,\cdot):\operatorname{Hom}(X_{0},X_{1})\to\operatorname{Hom}(X_{0},X_{2% })\quad\text{and}\quad m_{2}(\cdot,f):\operatorname{Hom}(X_{2},X_{3})\to% \operatorname{Hom}(X_{1},X_{3})$ are quasi-isomorphisms.
Definition 2.3. A non-unital $\mathbb{Z}$(resp. $\mathbb{Z}/2$)-graded $A_{\infty}\text{-}$category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is given by the following data: 1) A class of objects $Ob({\mathcal{C}}).$ 2) For any two objects $X_{1}$ and $X_{2},$ a $\mathbb{Z}$(resp. $\mathbb{Z}/2$)-graded vector space of morphisms $\operatorname{Hom}(X_{1},X_{2}).$ 3) For any sequence of objects $X_{0},\dots,X_{n},$ a map of graded vector spaces $m_{n}:\bigotimes\limits_{0\leq i\leq n-1}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{i+1})\to% \operatorname{Hom}(X_{0},X_{n})[2-n].$ This data us required to satisfy the following property: for each finite collection of objects $X_{0},\dots,X_{N},$ $N\geq 0,$ the graded vector space $\bigoplus\limits_{0\leq i,j\leq N}\operatorname{Hom}(X_{i},X_{j})$ equipped with operations $m_{n},$ becomes an $A_{\infty}\text{-}$algebra.
Definition 2.19. Two $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories ${\mathcal{C}}$ and ${\mathcal{D}}$ are called quasi-equivalent if there exists a sequence ${\mathcal{C}}_{0},{\mathcal{C}}_{1},\dots,{\mathcal{C}}_{n}$ of $A_{\infty}\text{-}$pre-categories with ${\mathcal{C}}_{0}={\mathcal{C}},$ ${\mathcal{C}}_{n}={\mathcal{D}},$ such that for each $o\leq i\leq n-1$ there exists a quasi-equivalence from ${\mathcal{C}}_{i}$ to ${\mathcal{C}}_{i+1}$ or vice versa.
Definition 2.2 A diagrammatic logic is a locally presentable functor $L$ such that its right adjoint $R$ is full and faithful. An inference system for $L$ is a morphism of limit sketches $\mathbf{e}\colon\mathbf{E}_{S}\to\mathbf{E}_{T}$ such that $L=L_{\mathbf{e}}$.
Definition 3.1 Let us consider two diagrammatic logics $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$. A morphism of diagrammatic logics $F\colon L_{1}\to L_{2}$ is a pair of locally presentable functors $(F_{S},F_{T})$ together with a natural isomorphism $F_{T}\circ L_{1}\cong L_{2}\circ F_{S}$. In practice, it is defined from inference systems $\mathbf{e}_{1}\colon\mathbf{E}_{S,1}\to\mathbf{E}_{T,1}$ for $L_{1}$ and $\mathbf{e}_{2}\colon\mathbf{E}_{S,2}\to\mathbf{E}_{T,2}$ for $L_{2}$ and from a pair of morphisms of limit sketches $\mathbf{e}_{S}\colon\mathbf{E}_{S,1}\to\mathbf{E}_{S,2}$ and $\mathbf{e}_{T}\colon\mathbf{E}_{T,1}\to\mathbf{E}_{T,2}$ which form a commutative diagram $\xymatrix@C=4pc@R=1.5pc{\mathbf{E}_{S,1}\ar[r]^{\mathbf{e}_{1}}\ar[d]_{\mathbf% {e}_{S}}&\mathbf{E}_{T,1}\ar[d]^{\mathbf{e}_{T}}\\ \mathbf{E}_{S,2}\ar[r]^{\mathbf{e}_{2}}&\mathbf{E}_{T,2}\\ }$ This defines the category of diagrammatic logics, $\mathbf{DiaLog}$.
Definition 2.1 An entailment for a diagrammatic logic $L\colon\mathbf{S}\to\mathbf{T}$ is a morphism $\tau\colon\Sigma\to\Sigma^{\prime}$ in $\mathbf{S}$ such that $L\tau$ is invertible in $\mathbf{T}$. This is denoted $\xymatrix{\Sigma\ar[r]^{\tau}&\Sigma^{\prime}\ar@<1ex>@{-->}[l]\\ }$. An instance $\kappa$ of a specification $\Sigma$ in a specification $\Sigma_{1}$ is a cospan in $\mathbf{S}$ made of a morphism $\sigma$ and an entailment $\tau$ $\xymatrix@C=4pc{\Sigma\ar[r]^{\sigma}&\Sigma^{\prime}_{1}\ar@{-->}@<-1ex>[r]&% \Sigma_{1}\ar[l]_{\tau}\\ }$
Definition 2.3 An inference rule $\rho$ with hypothesis $\mathcal{H}$ and conclusion $\mathcal{C}$ is an instance $\rho={\tau}\backslash{\sigma}\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{H}$ of the conclusion in the hypothesis, where $\sigma$ and $\tau$ are in $\mathcal{Y}(\mathbf{E})$. Given an inference rule $\rho={\tau}\backslash{\sigma}\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{H}$ and an instance $\kappa\colon\mathcal{H}\to\Sigma$ of the hypothesis $\mathcal{H}$ in a specification $\Sigma$, the corresponding inference step provides the instance $\kappa\circ\rho\colon\mathcal{C}\to\Sigma$ of the conclusion $\mathcal{C}$ in $\Sigma$. The commutative triangle in the category of fractions (on the left) is computed thanks to the commutative diagram in the category of specifications (on the right) where the square is a pushout. $\xymatrix@C=2pc{\mathcal{H}\ar[dr]_{\kappa}&&\mathcal{C}\ar[ll]_{\rho}\ar[dl]^% {\kappa\circ\rho}\\ &\Sigma&\\ }\qquad\qquad\xymatrix@C=1.5pc@R=1pc{\mathcal{H}\ar[dr]\ar[rr]^{\tau}&&% \mathcal{H}^{\prime}\ar[dr]\ar@{-->}@<1ex>[ll]&&\mathcal{C}\ar[ll]_{\sigma}\ar% [dl]\\ &\Sigma_{H}\ar@{-->}@<-1ex>[rd]\ar[rr]&&\Sigma_{C}\ar@{-->}@<1ex>[ld]\ar@{-->}% @<1ex>[ll]&\\ &&\Sigma\ar[lu]\ar[ru]&&\\ }$ A proof (or derivation, or derived rule) is the description of a morphism of theories as an instance composed from inference rules.
Definition 16 A homomorphism $E\rightarrow D$ of effect algebras is given by a function $f\colon E\rightarrow D$ between the underlying sets satisfying: • $x\mathrel{\bot}x^{\prime}$ in $E$ implies both $f(x)\mathrel{\bot}f(x^{\prime})$ in $D$ and $f(x\ovee x^{\prime})=f(x)\ovee f(x^{\prime})$; • $f(1)=1$. Effect algebras and their homomorphisms form a category, which we call $\mathbf{EA}$.
Definition 7 A semiring $S$ is called zerosumfree if $x+y=0$ implies both $x=0$ and $y=0$. It is integral if it has no zero divisors: $x\cdot y=0$ implies either $x=0$ or $y=0$. And it is called a semifield if it is non-trivial (i.e. $0\neq 1$), zerosumfree, integral and each non-zero element $s\in S$ has a multiplicative inverse $s^{-1}=\frac{1}{s}\in S$.
Definition 11 Let $S$ be a semiring and $\alpha\colon\mathcal{D}_{S}(X)\rightarrow X$ be an algebra of the monad $\mathcal{D}_{S}$, making $X$ convex. We write $(\sum_{i\leq n}s_{i}x_{i})\in\mathcal{D}_{S}(X)$ for an arbitrary convex combination. A subset $U\subseteq X$ is called a: • subalgebra if $\forall_{i\leq n}.\,x_{i}\in U$ implies $\alpha(\sum_{i}s_{i}x_{i})\in U$; • filter if $\alpha(\sum_{i}s_{i}x_{i})\in U$ implies $x_{i}\in U$, for each $i$ with $s_{i}\neq 0$; • prime filter if it is both a subalgebra and a filter. An element $x\in X$ is called extreme, or a boundary point, if $\{x\}$ is a prime filter. Often one writes $\partial X$ for the set of extreme points.
Definition 9 A convex set consists of a set $X$ together with a ternary operation $\langle-,-,-\rangle\colon[0,1]_{\mathbb{R}}\times X\times X\rightarrow X$ satisfying the following four requirements, for all $r\in[0,1]_{\mathbb{R}}$ and $x,y,z\in X$. 1. $\langle r,x,y\rangle=\langle 1-r,y,x\rangle$ 2. $\langle r,x,x\rangle=x$ 3. $\langle 0,x,y\rangle=y$ 4. $\langle r,x,\langle s,y,z\rangle\rangle=\langle r+(1-r)s,\;\langle\frac{r}{(r+% (1-r)s)},x,y\rangle,\;z\rangle$, assuming that $(r+(1-r)s)\neq 0$. A morphism of convex structures $(X,\langle-,-,-\rangle_{X})\rightarrow(Y,\langle-,-,-\rangle_{Y})$ consists of an “affine” function $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ satisfying $f(\langle r,x,x^{\prime}\rangle_{X})=\langle r,f(x),f(x^{\prime})\rangle_{Y}$, for all $r\in[0,1]_{\mathbb{R}}$ and $x,x^{\prime}\in X$. This yields a category $\mathbf{Conv}$.
Definition 14 An effect algebra is a partial commutative monoid $(E,0,\ovee)$ with an orthosupplement. The latter is a unary operation $(-)^{\perp}\colon E\rightarrow E$ satisfying: 1. $x^{\perp}\in E$ is the unique element in $E$ with $x\ovee x^{\perp}=1$, where $1=0^{\perp}$; 2. $x\mathrel{\bot}1\Rightarrow x=0$.
Definition 1 A monad (on $\mathbf{Sets}$) consists of an endofunctor $T\colon\mathbf{Sets}\rightarrow\mathbf{Sets}$ together with two natural transformations: a unit $\eta\colon\mathrm{id}\Rightarrow T$ and multiplication $\mu\colon T^{2}\Rightarrow T$. These are required to make the following diagrams commute, for $X\in\mathbf{Sets}$. $\xymatrix@C-1pc@R-.5pc{T(X)\ar[rr]^{-}{\eta_{T(X)}}\ar@{=}[drr]&&T^{2}(X)\ar[d% ]^{\mu_{X}}&&T(X)\ar[ll]_{T(\eta_{X})}\ar@{=}[dll]&&T^{3}(X)\ar[rr]^{-}{\mu_{T% (X)}}\ar[d]_{T(\mu_{X})}&&T^{2}(X)\ar[d]^{\mu_{X}}\\ &&T(X)&&&&T^{2}\ar[rr]_{\mu_{X}}&&T(X)}$
Definition 3 Given a monad $T=(T,\eta,\mu)$ as in the previous definition, one defines an algebra of this monad as a map $\alpha\colon T(X)\rightarrow X$ satisfying two requirements, expressed via the diagrams: $\xymatrix@C-1pc@R-.5pc{X\ar[rr]^{-}{\eta_{X}}\ar@{=}[drr]&&T(X)\ar[d]^{\alpha}% &&T^{2}(X)\ar[rr]^{-}{\mu_{X}}\ar[d]_{T(\alpha)}&&T(X)\ar[d]^{\alpha}\\ &&X&&T(X)\ar[rr]_{-}{\alpha}&&X}$ We shall write $\textsl{Alg}(T)$ for the category with such algebras as objects. A morphism $\smash{\big{(}T(X)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\alpha}}{{\rightarrow}}X\big{)}% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\longrightarrow}}\big{(}T(Y)\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\beta}}{{\rightarrow}}Y\big{)}}$ in $\textsl{Alg}(T)$ is a map $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ between the underlying sets satisfying $f\mathrel{\circ}\alpha=\beta\mathrel{\circ}T(f)$.
Definition 1. Let $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}S})$ be the bounded derived category of graded $S$-modules and $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{\Sigma}S})$ the full triangulated subcategory of graded $J_{\Sigma}$-torsion $S$-modules, i.e. any object is isomorphic to a complex of $J_{\Sigma}$-torsion modules. The quotient category, $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm qgr}_{\Sigma}S})=\frac{D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}S})}{D^{b}(% \mathop{{\rm tor}_{\Sigma}S})},$ is defined by localization along the multiplicative system of morphisms $s$ that fit into distinguished triangles $A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle s}}{{\longrightarrow}}B\longrightarrow C% \longrightarrow A[1],$ where $A,B\in D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}S})$ and $C\in D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{\Sigma}S})$.
Definition 3. Let $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{\hat{\Sigma}}\hat{S}})$ be the full triangulated subcategory of $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$ consisting of graded $J_{\hat{\Sigma}}$-torsion modules, and consider its image in $D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$, that is $D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{\hat{\Sigma}}\hat{S}}):=\pi_{\rm sg}D^{b}(% \mathop{{\rm tor}_{\hat{\Sigma}}\hat{S}})$. This is a full triangulated subcategory of $D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$. We define the quotient category $D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm qgr}_{\hat{\Sigma}}\hat{S}}):=\frac{D_{\rm sg}(\mathop% {{\rm gr}\hat{S}})}{D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{\hat{\Sigma}}\hat{S}})}.$
Definition 4. Let $\hat{S}=\hat{R}/(W)\hat{R}$, and $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$ as well as $D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$ be as in Definition 2. Take any maximal cone $\hat{\Phi}$ in the secondary fan of $\mathbb{P}_{\hat{\Sigma}}$. Let $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{\hat{\Phi}}\hat{S}})$ be the full triangulated subcategory of $J_{\hat{\Phi}}$-torsion modules in $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$, and $D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{\hat{\Phi}}\hat{S}})$ its image in $D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$. Then we define the quotient ${\mathcal{C}}_{\hat{\Phi}}=D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm qgr}_{\hat{\Phi}}\hat{S}}):% =\frac{D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})}{D_{\rm sg}(\mathop{{\rm tor}_{% \hat{\Phi}}\hat{S}})}.$
Definition 2. Let $D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$ be the derived category of graded $\hat{S}$-modules, and ${\rm Perf}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})$ the full triangulated subcategory of perfect complexes, i.e. bounded complexes of free modules. The singularity category is the quotient $D_{{\rm sg}}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}}):=\frac{D^{b}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})}% {{\rm Perf}(\mathop{{\rm gr}\hat{S}})}.$
Definition 5.3. Let $(\mathcal{C},c)$ be a braided tensor category, and let $G$ be an abelian group. A braiding for a central coherent $G$-action over $\mathcal{C}$ is a triple $(\theta^{\sigma},\overline{\theta}^{\sigma},t_{\sigma,\tau})_{\sigma,\tau\in G}$, where • $\theta^{\sigma},\overline{\theta}^{\sigma}:\mathrm{id}_{\mathcal{C}}\to\mathrm% {id}_{\mathcal{C}}$ are monoidal natural isomorphisms, • $t_{\sigma,\tau}:\chi_{\sigma,\tau}\to\chi_{\tau,\sigma}$ are isomorphisms in $\mathcal{Z}(\mathcal{C})$ for all $\sigma,\tau\in G$, such that $\theta^{e}=\overline{\theta}^{e}=\mathrm{id}$, $\theta_{I}^{\sigma}=\mathrm{id}_{I}$, $t_{\sigma,e}=t_{e,\sigma}=\mathrm{id}_{I}$, and the diagrams $\diagram\node{Z\otimes U_{\sigma,\tau}}\arrow{se,r}{((\overline{\theta}_{Z}^{% \sigma\tau})^{-1}\overline{\theta}_{Z}^{\sigma}\overline{\theta}_{Z}^{\tau})% \otimes\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma,\tau}}}\arrow{e,t}{\chi_{\sigma,\tau}(Z)}\node{U% _{\sigma,\tau}\otimes Z}\arrow{s,r}{c_{U_{\sigma,\tau},Z}}\\ \node{}\node{Z\otimes U_{\sigma,\tau}}$ $\diagram\node{Z\otimes U_{\sigma,\tau}}\arrow{se,r}{((\theta_{Z}^{\sigma\tau})% ^{-1}\theta_{Z}^{\sigma}\theta_{Z}^{\tau})\otimes\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma,\tau}}% }\arrow{e,t}{c_{U_{\sigma,\tau},Z}}\node{U_{\sigma,\tau}\otimes Z}\arrow{s,r}{% \chi_{\sigma,\tau}(Z)}\\ \node{}\node{Z\otimes U_{\sigma,\tau}}$ $\diagram\node{}\node{U_{\sigma,\tau}U_{\sigma\tau,\rho}}\arrow[2]{e,t}{\theta_% {U_{\sigma,\tau}}^{\rho}\otimes t_{\sigma\tau,\rho}}\node{}\node{U_{\sigma,% \tau}U_{\rho,\sigma\tau}}\arrow{se,l}{w_{\rho,\sigma,\tau}}\\ \node{U_{\tau,\rho}U_{\sigma,\tau\rho}}\arrow{ne,l}{\omega_{\sigma,\tau,\rho}}% \arrow{se,r}{t_{\tau,\rho}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma,\rho\tau}}}\node{}% \node{}\node{}\node{U_{\rho,\sigma}U_{\sigma\rho,\tau}}\\ \node{}\node{U_{\rho,\tau}U_{\sigma,\rho\tau}}\arrow[2]{e,t}{\omega_{\sigma,% \rho,\tau}}\node{}\node{U_{\sigma,\rho}U_{\sigma\rho,\tau}}\arrow{ne,r}{t_{% \sigma,\tau}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma\rho,\tau}}}$ $\diagram\node{}\node{U_{\tau,\rho}U_{\sigma,\tau\rho}}\arrow[2]{e,t}{\overline% {\theta}^{\sigma}_{U_{\tau,\rho}}\otimes t_{\sigma,\tau\rho}}\node{}\node{U_{% \tau,\rho}U_{\tau\rho,\sigma}}\arrow{se,l}{\omega_{\tau,\rho,\sigma}^{-1}}\\ \node{U_{\sigma,\tau}U_{\sigma\tau,\rho}}\arrow{ne,l}{\omega^{-1}_{\sigma,\tau% ,\rho}}\arrow{se,r}{t_{\sigma,\tau}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma\tau,\rho}}}% \node{}\node{}\node{}\node{U_{\rho,\sigma}U_{\tau,\rho\sigma}}\\ \node{}\node{U_{\tau,\sigma}U_{\tau\sigma,\rho}}\arrow[2]{e,t}{\omega_{\tau,% \sigma,\rho}^{-1}}\node{}\node{U_{\sigma,\rho}U_{\tau,\sigma\rho}}\arrow{ne,r}% {t_{\sigma,\rho}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{U_{\tau,\sigma\rho}}}$ commute for all $\sigma,\tau,\rho\in G,Z\in\mathcal{C}$ (where tensor symbols among objects have been omitted as a space-saving measure).
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{B}=(\overline{\circ},I,\alpha)$ and $\mathcal{B}^{\prime}=(\overline{\circ},I^{\prime},\alpha^{\prime})$ be bicategories. A pseudofunctor $\Phi=(F,\phi)$ from $\mathcal{B}$ to $\mathcal{B}^{\prime}$ consists of the following data • a function $F:\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})\to\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B}^{\prime})$, $A\mapsto F(A)$, • for each pair $A,B\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$, functors $F_{AB}:\mathcal{B}(A,B)\to\mathcal{B}^{\prime}(F(A),F(B)),\ \ S\mapsto F(S),\ % f\mapsto F(f),$ • for each triple $A,B,C\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$, a natural isomorphism $\psi^{ABC}:F_{AC}(-\overline{\circ}^{ABC}-)\to F_{AB}(-)\overline{\circ}^{F(A)% F(B)F(C)}F_{BC}(-),$ Subject to the following axioms (i) $F_{AA}(I_{A})=I^{\prime}_{F(A)}$, (ii) if $(S,T,U)$ is an object in $\mathcal{B}(A,B)\times\mathcal{B}(B,C)\times\mathcal{B}(C,D)$, the following diagram commutes (where the indexes have been omitted) $\diagram\node{F(S\overline{\circ}(T\overline{\circ}U))}\arrow{s,l}{\psi}\arrow% [3]{e,t}{F(\alpha)}\node[2]{}\node{F((S\overline{\circ}T)\overline{\circ}U)}% \arrow{s,r}{\psi}\\ \node{F(S)\overline{\circ}F(T\overline{\circ}U)}\arrow{s,l}{\mathrm{id}% \overline{\circ}\psi}\node[2]{}\node{F(S\overline{\circ}T)\overline{\circ}F(U)% }\arrow{s,r}{\psi\overline{\circ}\mathrm{id}}\\ \node{F(S)\overline{\circ}(F(T)\overline{\circ}F(U))}\arrow[3]{e,t}{\alpha^{% \prime}}\node[2]{}\node{(F(S)\overline{\circ}F(T))\overline{\circ}F(U)}\\ $ (iii) if $S$ is an object in $\mathcal{B}(A,B)$, then $\psi_{S,I_{B}}=\mathrm{id}_{F(S)}$ and $\psi_{I_{A},S}=F(S)$, for each pair of 0-cells $A,B\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a tensor category and let $F:\underline{G}\to\underline{2Out_{\otimes}(\mathcal{C})}$ be an incoherent outer $G$-action. A coherent outer $G$-action associated to $F$, is a crossed system $(\{\widetilde{\sigma}\}_{\sigma\in G},\chi,\omega)$ associated to $F$, such that for the pseudonatural isomorphisms $\chi_{\sigma,\tau}$ and the invertible modifications $\omega_{\sigma,\tau,\rho}$, the diagram $\diagram\node{\sigma_{*}(\tau_{*}(U_{\rho,\mu})U_{\tau,\rho\mu})U_{\sigma,\tau% \rho\mu}}\arrow{s,r}{\psi^{\sigma_{*}}_{\tau_{*}(U_{\rho,\mu}),U_{\tau,\rho\mu% }}\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma,\tau\rho\mu}}}\arrow{e,t}{\sigma_{*}(\omega_{\tau,% \rho,\mu})\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma,\tau\rho\mu}}}\node{\sigma_{*}(U_{\tau,\rho}U% _{\tau\rho,\mu})U_{\sigma,\tau\rho\mu}}\arrow{e,t}{\psi^{\sigma_{*}}_{U_{\tau,% \rho},U_{\tau\rho,\mu}}\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma,\tau\rho\mu}}}\node{\sigma_{*}(U% _{\sigma,\tau})\sigma_{*}(U_{\tau\rho,\mu})U_{\sigma,\tau\rho\mu}}\arrow{s,r}{% \mathrm{id}_{\sigma_{*}(U_{\sigma,\tau})}\omega_{\sigma,\tau\rho,\mu}}\\ \node{\sigma_{*}(\tau_{*}(U_{\sigma,\mu}))\sigma_{*}(U_{\tau,\rho\mu})U_{% \sigma,\tau\rho\mu}}\arrow{s,r}{\mathrm{id}_{\sigma_{*}(\tau_{*}(U_{\sigma,% \tau}))}\omega_{\sigma,\tau,\rho\mu}}\node{}\node{\sigma_{*}(U_{\tau,\rho})U_{% \sigma,\tau\rho}U_{\sigma\tau\rho,\mu}}\arrow{s,r}{\omega_{\sigma,\tau,\rho}% \mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma\tau\rho,\mu}}}\\ \node{\sigma_{*}(\tau_{*}(U_{\rho,\mu}))U_{\sigma,\tau}U_{\sigma\tau,\rho\mu}}% \arrow{e,t}{\chi_{\sigma,\tau}(U_{\rho,\mu})\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma\tau,\rho\mu% }}}\node{U_{\sigma,\tau}(\sigma\tau)_{*}(U_{\rho,\mu})U_{\sigma\tau,\rho\mu}}% \arrow{e,t}{\mathrm{id}_{U_{\sigma,\tau}}\omega_{\sigma\tau,\rho,\mu}}\node{U_% {\sigma,\tau}U_{\sigma\tau,\rho}U_{\sigma\tau\rho,\mu}}$ commutes for all $\sigma,\tau,\rho,\mu\in G$ (where tensor symbols among objects and arrows have been omitted as a space-saving measure).
Definition 2.9. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a tensor category graded over a group $G$. We shall say that $\mathcal{C}=\bigoplus_{\sigma\in G}\mathcal{C}_{\sigma}$ is a crossed product tensor category over $G$, if every $\mathcal{C}_{\sigma}$ has a multiplicatively invertible object.
Definition 3.1. Let $G$ be a group and let $\mathcal{C}$ be a monoidal category. An incoherent outer $G$-action over $\mathcal{C}$, is an op-monoidal functor $*:\underline{G}\to\underline{2Out_{\otimes}(\mathcal{C})}$. Two incoherent outer $G$-actions are equivalent if the associated monoidal functors are monoidally equivalent.
Definition 2.4. Let $F,G:\mathcal{B}_{0}\to\mathcal{B}_{1}$ be pseudofunctors between bicategories $\mathcal{B}_{0}$ and $\mathcal{B}_{1}$. A pseudonatural transformation $\sigma:F\to G$, consists of the following data • for each $A\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B}_{0})$, 1-cells $\sigma_{A}\in\mathcal{B}_{1}(F(A),G(A))$, • for each pair $A,B\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B}_{0})$, and each 1-cell $V\in\mathcal{B}_{0}(A,B)$ a natural isomorphism $\sigma_{V}:F^{AB}(V)\overline{\circ}^{F(A)F(B)G(B)}\sigma_{B}\to\sigma_{A}% \overline{\circ}^{F(A)G(A)G(B)}G^{AB}(V),$ such that $\sigma_{I_{A}}=\mathrm{id}_{I_{A}}$ for all $A\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B}_{0})$ and for all $S\in\mathcal{B}_{0}(A,B)$, $T\in\mathcal{B}_{0}(B,C)$, the following diagram $\diagram\node{F(ST)\sigma}\arrow{s,l}{\psi^{F}\overline{\circ}\mathrm{id}_{% \sigma}}\arrow[2]{e,t}{\sigma_{ST}}\node[2]{\sigma G(ST)}\arrow{s,r}{\mathrm{% id}_{\sigma}\overline{\circ}\psi^{G}}\\ \node{F(S)F(T)\sigma}\arrow{e,t}{\mathrm{id}_{F(S)}\overline{\circ}\sigma_{T}}% \node{F(S)\sigma G(T)}\arrow{e,t}{\sigma_{S}\overline{\circ}\mathrm{id}_{G(T)}% }\node{\sigma G(S)G(T)}$ commutes (where associativity constraint, indexes, and the symbols $\overline{\circ}$ between objects have been omitted as a space-saving measure).
Definition 2.1. A bicategory $\mathcal{B}$ consists of the following data • a set $\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$ (with elements $A,B,\ldots$ called 0-cells ), • for each pair $A,B\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$, a category $\mathcal{B}(A,B)$ (with objects $V,W,\ldots$ called 1-cells and morphisms $f,g,\ldots$ called 2-cells), • for each $A,B,C\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$, a bifunctor $\overline{\circ}^{ABC}:\mathcal{B}(A,B)\times\mathcal{B}(B,C)\to\mathcal{B}(A,% C),$ • for each 0-cell $A\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$, a 1-cell $I_{A}\in\mathcal{B}(A,A)$, • for each $A,B,C,D\in\text{Obj}(\mathcal{B})$, natural isomorphisms (constraint of associativity) $\displaystyle\alpha^{A,B,C,D}:-\overline{\circ}^{ABD}(-\overline{\circ}^{BCD}-)$ $\displaystyle\to(-\overline{\circ}^{ABC}-)\overline{\circ}^{ACD}-:$ $\displaystyle\mathcal{B}(A,B)\times\mathcal{B}(B,C)\times\mathcal{B}(C,D)$ $\displaystyle\to\mathcal{B}(A,D).$ Subject to the following axioms • coherence of the associativity: if $(S,T,U,V)$ is an object in $\mathcal{B}(A,B)\times\mathcal{B}(B,C)\times\mathcal{B}(C,D)\times\mathcal{B}(% D,E)$, the next diagram commutes $\diagram\node{}\node{S\overline{\circ}(T\overline{\circ}(U\overline{\circ}V))}% \arrow{sw,l}{\alpha_{S,T,U\overline{\circ}V}}\arrow{se,l}{\mathrm{id}\overline% {\circ}\alpha_{T,U,V}}\node{}\\ \node{(S\overline{\circ}T)\overline{\circ}(U\overline{\circ}V)}\arrow{s,r}{% \alpha_{S\overline{\circ}T,U,V}}\node{}\node{S\overline{\circ}((T\overline{% \circ}U)\overline{\circ}V)}\arrow{s,r}{\alpha_{S,T\overline{\circ}U,V}}\\ \node{((S\overline{\circ}T)\overline{\circ}U)\overline{\circ}V}\node{}\node{(S% \overline{\circ}(T\overline{\circ}U))\overline{\circ}V}\arrow[2]{w,t}{\alpha_{% S,T,U}\overline{\circ}\mathrm{id}}$ • coherence of the unity $\alpha_{S,I_{B},T}=\mathrm{id}_{S\overline{\circ}T}.$
Definition 5.1. A coherent outer $G$-action shall be called central if $\sigma_{*}=\mathrm{id}_{\mathcal{C}}$ for all $\sigma\in G$.
Definition 2.1. A type-theoretic fibration category is a category $\mathscr{C}$ with : (1) A terminal object 1. (2) A subcategory of fibrations containing all the isomorphisms and all the morphisms with codomain 1. A morphism is called an acyclic cofibration if it has the left lifting property with respect to all fibrations. (3) All pullbacks of fibrations exist and are fibrations. (4) The pullback functor along any fibration has a right adjoint that preserves fibrations. (5) Every morphism factors as an acyclic cofibration followed by a fibration.
Definition 4.2. Given a universe $p\colon\widetilde{U}\rightarrow U$ in a type-theoretic fibration category, a small fibration, or a $U$-small fibration, is a pullback of $p$.
Definition 2.2. A type-theoretic model category is a model category $\mathscr{M}$ satisfying the following additional properties. (i) The pullback functor along a fibration preserves acyclic cofibrations. (ii) The pullback functor $g^{*}$ along a fibration $g$ has a right adjoint $\Pi_{g}$.
Definition 4.1. A fibration $p:\widetilde{U}\twoheadrightarrow U$ in a type-theoretic fibration category $\mathscr{C}$ is a universe if the following hold. (i) Pullbacks of $p$ are closed under composition and contain the identities. (ii) If $f:B\twoheadrightarrow A$ and $g:A\twoheadrightarrow C$ are pullbacks of $p$, so is $\Pi_{g}f\twoheadrightarrow C$. (iii) If $A\twoheadrightarrow C$ and $B\twoheadrightarrow C$ are pullbacks of $p$, then any morphism $f:A\to B$ over $C$ factors as an acyclic cofibration followed by a pullback of $p$.
Definition 2.4. One can define several topologies on the dual $E^{\prime}$ of a lcs $E$. We will make use of : • The strong dual $E^{\prime}_{\beta}$, endowed with the strong topology $\beta(E^{\prime},E)$ of uniform convergence on bounded subsets of $E$. • The Arens dual $E^{\prime}_{c}$ endowed with the topology $\gamma(E^{\prime},E)$ of uniform convergence on absolutely convex compact subsets of $E$. • The Mackey dual $E^{\prime}_{\mu}$, endowed with the Mackey topology of uniform convergence on absolutely convex weakly compact subsets of $E$. • The weak dual $E^{\prime}_{\sigma}$ endowed with the weak topology $\sigma(E^{\prime},E)$ of simple convergence on points of $E$. • The $\varepsilon$-dual $E^{\prime}_{\varepsilon}$ of a dual $E=F^{\prime}$ is the dual $E^{\prime}$ endowed with the topology of uniform convergence on equicontinuous sets in $F^{\prime}$. Remember that when it is considered as a set of linear forms acting on $E^{\prime}$, $E$ is always endowed with the topology of uniform convergence on equicontinuous parts of $E^{\prime}$, equivalent to the original topology of $E$, hence $(E^{\prime}_{\mu})^{\prime}_{\epsilon}\simeq(E^{\prime}_{c})^{\prime}_{% \epsilon}\simeq(E^{\prime}_{\sigma})^{\prime}_{\epsilon}\simeq E$. A lcs is said to be reflexive when it is topologically equal to its strong double dual $(E^{\prime}_{\beta})^{\prime}_{\beta}$.
Definition 2.2. Consider $E$, $F$, $G$ topological vector spaces and $h:E\times F\mapsto G$ a bilinear map. • $h$ is continuous if it is continuous from $E\times F$ endowed with the product topology to $G$. • $h$ is separately continuous if for any $x\in E$ and $y\in F$, $h(x,.)$ is continuous from $F$ to $G$ and $h(.,y)$ is continuous from $E$ to $G$. • Consider $\mathcal{B}_{1}$ (resp. $\mathcal{B}_{2}$) a bornology on $E$ (resp. $F$). Then $h$ is said to be $\mathcal{B}_{1}$,$\mathcal{B}_{2}$ hypocontinuous [Schwartz2] if for every $0$-neighbourhood $W$ in $G$, every bounded set $A_{E}$ in $E$, and every bounded set $A_{F}$ in $F$, there are $0$-neighbourhoods $V_{F}\subset F$ and $V_{E}\subset E$ such that $h(A_{E}\times V_{F})\subset W$ and $h(V_{E}\times A_{F})\subset W$. When no precision is given, an hypocontinuous bilinear map is a map hypocontinuous for both Von-Neumann bornologies.
Definition 2.1. Consider $E$ a vector space. A bornology on $E$ is a collection of sets (the bounded sets of $E$) such that the union of all those sets covers E, and such that the collection is stable under inclusion and finite unions.
Definition 2.5. A $*$-autonomous category is a symmetric monoidal closed category $(\mathcal{C},\otimes_{\mathcal{C}},1_{\mathcal{C}},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathcal{C}})$ with an object $\perp$ giving an equivalence of categories $(\cdot)^{*}=[\cdot,\perp]_{\mathcal{C}}:\mathcal{C}^{op}\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt% \hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749% 943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt% \raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt% \hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.% 0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt% \hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057% pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont\char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0% .0pt\raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114% pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox{\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt % depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces}}}\>\mathcal{C}$ and with the canonical map $d_{A}:A\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}\ignorespaces{\hbox{% \kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.9% 99947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$% \scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5% pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0% pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}% }\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont% \char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{% \hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox% {\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}% \ignorespaces}}}\>(A^{*})^{*}$ being a natural isomorphism.
Definition 2.3. Consider $E$ and $F$ two lcs. • The projective tensor product $E\otimes_{\pi}F$ is the finest locally convex topology on $E\otimes F$ making $E\times F\rightarrow E\otimes_{\pi}F$ continuous. • The inductive tensor product $E\otimes_{i}F$ is the finest locally convex topology on $E\otimes F$ making $E\times F\rightarrow E\otimes_{i}F$ separately continuous. • The hypocontinous tensor product $E\otimes_{\beta}F$ is the finest locally convex topology on $E\otimes F$ making $E\times F\rightarrow E\otimes_{\beta}F$ hypocontinuous. • The $\gamma$ tensor product $E\otimes_{\gamma}F$ is the finest locally convex topology on $E\otimes F$ making $E\times F\rightarrow E\otimes_{\gamma}F$ $\gamma$-hypocontinuous. • Suppose that $E$ and $F$ are duals. The $\varepsilon$-hypocontinous tensor product $E\otimes_{\beta e}F$ is the finest locally convex topology on $E\otimes F$ making $E\times F\rightarrow E\otimes_{\beta e}F$ $\varepsilon$-hypocontinuous. • Consider $\mathcal{B}_{1}$ (resp. $\mathcal{B}_{2}$) a bornology on $E$ (resp. $F$).The $\mathcal{B}_{1}-\mathcal{B}_{2}$-hypocontinous tensor product $E\otimes_{\mathcal{B}_{1},\mathcal{B}_{2}}F$ is the finest locally convex topology on $E\otimes F$ making $E\times F\rightarrow E\otimes_{\mathcal{B}_{1},\mathcal{B}_{2}}F$ $\mathcal{B}_{1},\mathcal{B}_{2}$-hypocontinuous.
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category, $\operatorname{Aut}(\mathcal{C})$ be the group of isomorphisms $\mathcal{C}\overset{\cong}{\to}\mathcal{C}$, and $G\xrightarrow{\rho}\operatorname{Aut}(\mathcal{C})$ be an action of $G$ on the category $\mathcal{C}$. Then the semidirect product $\mathcal{C}\rtimes G$ has objects the objects of $\mathcal{C}$ and morphisms pairs $(\varphi,g)$ with $\varphi$ a $\mathcal{C}$-morphism and $g$ a group element; if the source and target of $\varphi$ are $x$ and $y$ then the source and target of $(\varphi,g)$ are $\rho_{g^{-1}}(x)$ and $y$. Composition is given by $(\varphi,g)\circ(\psi,h)=(\varphi\circ\rho_{g}(\psi),gh).$
Definition 5.3. If $(A,\sigma)\in\mathbf{isSet}$, define $\widetilde{\mathfrak{C}}(A,\sigma)\coloneqq(\mathfrak{C}(A),\sigma^{\prime})% \in\mathbf{isCat}.$ If $(X,\tau)$ is an anti-involutive simplicially-enriched category, define $\widetilde{N}_{hc}(X,\tau)\coloneqq(N_{hc}(X),\tau^{\prime})\in\mathbf{isSet}.$
